ty, criminality, resistance, and the memory of the occupation. This local case study calls into question overly-patriotic readings of this experience, and suggests a new conceptual vocabulary to help understand certain civilian behaviours under military occupation. Drawing on extensive primary documentation, this book proposes that a dominant 'occupied culture' existed among locals: a moral-patriotic framework, born of both pre-war socio-cultural norms and daily interaction with the enemy, that guided conduct and was especially concerned with what was considered acceptable and unacceptable behaviour.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc/4.0  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aCivilians in warzFrance, NorthernxHistoryy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xSocial aspectszFrance, Northern. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918zFrance, Northern. 7aHISTORY / Social History.2bisacsh  aCollaboration.  aComplicity.  aCriminality.  aCulture.  aDisunity.  aMisconduct.  aOccupation.  aResistance.1 aConnolly, James E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packagez978311128277040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/9781526117816zOpen Access7040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526117816zOpen Access70423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526117816/original  a978-3-11-128277-0 Manchester University Press 2018 eBook-Packageb2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-GOA